  "headline_findings": [
    "CDA is the fastest kernel across every measured (B, N) except (B=1, N=4K) where KIVI narrowly wins (96.7 vs 158.2 μs — fixed HMMA setup cost).",
    "At N≥16K, CDA beats all baselines: vs FA2 1.08-1.60×, vs QuaRot 1.97-9.16×, vs KVQuant 4.4-6.2× (B=1), vs KIVI 1.89-3.18×.",
    "Speedup vs KIVI (best GQA-native baseline) stabilizes around 2.5-3× at large (B, N) — tracking the ~2.8× memory-per-token advantage.",
    "QuaRot's Int4 kernel is actually SLOWER than its own FP16 at B=1 (0.76-0.87×) — direct evidence of dequantize-then-attend overhead that CDA avoids.",
    "At B=64 N=64K, KIVI OOMs on 48GB A6000 while CDA runs cleanly at 17ms — CDA's 2.8× smaller KV per token translates into strictly larger serving capacity.",
    "All baselines (QuaRot/KVQuant/KIVI) follow the dequantize-then-attend pattern. CDA's compute-on-compressed-indices is the unique kernel-level contribution."
